        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Ogle’s reply to CD’s letter of 25 March [1871] has not been found. CD’s ‘fib’ was to ask Ogle for information ‘in relation to a new point for observation’. CD had not mentioned the platysma myoides to avoid prejudicing Ogle’s response.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7622.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to William Ogle, 25 March [1871]</ref> and n. 9.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3643.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">James Paget</ref> and probably to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref>, who was studying medicine at St George’s Hospital, London (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5933.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi></ref>). Paget was suffering from blood poisoning as the result of an infection received during a post mortem examination he carried out in February 1871. His condition had worsened so that by this time he was thought to be near death. (See S. Paget ed. 1901, pp. 244–6.)</note>
        </div>        
            
